start.narrative:
Bug report: 'Discount codes aren't applied correctly. Some customers are being overcharged.'

You open the checkout function and find:

function procOrd(usrId, itmLst, dscCd) {
  const usr = getUsr(usrId);
  const ttl = calcTtl(itmLst);
  const dsc = getDsc(dscCd);
  const amt = ttl - (ttl * dsc.pct) + shpCst(usr.addr);
  return chrgUsr(usr.pmtMthd, amt);
}

What's your first reaction?

rewrite-first.narrative:
Smart instinct! You rename everything clearly. Now the formula is readable:

const amount = total - (total * discount.percent) + shippingCost;

With clear names, the logic is exposed. Can you see the discount bug?

end-good.narrative:
Fixed! The formula now reads:
const amount = total - (total * discount.percent / 100) + shippingCost;

A $100 order with 20% off: 100 - (100 * 20/100) + shipping = $80 + shipping. You also rename all the abbreviated variables so the next developer won't have to decode them.
